  "prompt": "Can we do court marriage in any state?",
  "response": "In India, court marriages can be performed in any state under the Special Marriage Act, 1954. This law allows any couple, regardless of religion, caste, or community, to marry in a civil ceremony. The couple must fulfill certain conditions and provide necessary documents to the court, such as:\n\n1. **Notice of Marriage**: A notice needs to be filed at the relevant marriage registrar office.\n2. **Documents Required**: Proof of identity, age, and marital status (like Aadhar card, passport, etc.), along with passport-sized photographs.\n3. **Witnesses**: Typically, two witnesses are required to be present at the time of the marriage.\n\nAfter the notice is published, if there are no objections, the marriage can be solemnized after 30 days. \n\nIt's advisable to consult with the local marriage registrar or legal expert in the respective state where you wish to get married to understand specific procedures and requirements.",
